10nm intel fab is more or less equivalent to 7nm TSMC fab.
Making a big deal about how 10nm > 7nm making it sound like intel is two generations behind is disingenuous. Sure, sucks for intel. They are a generation behind now, one generation that is, not two.


Even TSMC claim that their 7nm process is supposed to compete with intel's 10nm process.
Check out the graph on this article comparing transistor density of both fab processes: https://www.techcenturion.com/7nm-10nm-14nm-fabrication

snippet.textDisplay: Gate length has been stagnant at 22nm~ since the introduction of FinFET, 22, 16, 14, 10, 7, 6nm etc etc all mean absolutely nothing and are just marketing terms since finFET, so to claim that TSMCs 7nm is "better" than 10nm, by anything other than the fact that TSMC were able to ship their process would be falling in to the trap of what TSMCs marketing wants you to believe, Intels "10nm", has 54nm CPP, 36nm MMP, while TSMCs 7nm is 55 nm CCP, and 40nm MMP, TSMCs 7nm transistor density is actually LOWER than Intels 10nm by about 5%.
snippet.textOriginal: Gate length has been stagnant at 22nm~ since the introduction of FinFET, 22, 16, 14, 10, 7, 6nm etc etc all mean absolutely nothing and are just marketing terms since finFET, so to claim that TSMCs 7nm is "better" than 10nm, by anything other than the fact that TSMC were able to ship their process would be falling in to the trap of what TSMCs marketing wants you to believe, Intels "10nm", has 54nm CPP, 36nm MMP, while TSMCs 7nm is 55 nm CCP, and 40nm MMP, TSMCs 7nm transistor density is actually LOWER than Intels 10nm by about 5%.
